a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 How many squares have all four vertices on the 5 by 5 rectangular grid of dots below? Two such squares are displayed. [asy]
size(50);
for(int i = 0; i < 5; ++i){

for(int j = 0; j < 5; ++j){

dot((i,j));

}
}
draw((0,4)--(1,4)--(1,3)--(0,3)--cycle,linewidth(0.7));
draw((2,0)--(4,1)--(3,3)--(1,2)--cycle,linewidth(0.7));
[/asy] The final Answer is 50
 ### Proof
 Identify all the possible sizes of squares and count the number of squares of each size separately. \[ \begin{array}{cc} \text{Size} & \text{number of squares} \\ \hline \rule{0pt}{12pt}1\times 1 & 16 \\
 2 \times 2 & 9 \\ 3 \times 3 & 4 \\ 4 \times 4 & 1 \\ \sqrt{2}\times\sqrt{2} & 9 \\ \sqrt{5}\times\sqrt{5} & 8 \\ \sqrt{8}\times\sqrt{8} & 1 \\ \sqrt{10}\times\sqrt{10} & 2 \end{array} \] The sum of the numbers in the second column is $\boxed{50}$.
 Note: the possible side lengths of a square drawn on a square grid with $n^2$ dots are the real numbers of the form $\sqrt{x^2+y^2}$ where $x$ and $y$ are nonnegative integers satisfying $x+y\leq n-1$.
 *)

theorem
fixes squares :: nat
assumes h0 : "squares = (\<Sum>(i, j, k) \<in> {0..<5} \<times> {0..<5} \<times> {1..<5}. count_squares i j k)"
and h1 : "\<forall>i j k. count_squares i j k = (if i + k < 5 \<and> j + k < 5 then 1 else 0)"
shows  "squares = 50"
 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer

